@type = ("horizontal","horizontal","vertical");

@perm = NchooseK(3,3);
@eqn = @eqn[@perm];
@ans = @ans[@perm];
@type = @type[@perm];


##########################################
#  Main text

BEGIN_TEXT

Determine whether each function below has a horizontal or vertical asymptote, and find the equation of the asymptote if it exists.  Enter ${BITALIC}NONE${EITALIC} if there is no asymptote.
$BR
$BR
(a) $eqn[0] has a 
\{ pop_up_list(["?","horizontal","vertical","none"]) \}
asymptote with equation \{ ans_rule(10) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("equations") \}
$BR
$BR
(b) $eqn[1] has a
\{ pop_up_list(["?","horizontal","vertical","none"]) \}
asymptote with equation \{ ans_rule(10) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("equations") \}
$BR
$BR
(c) $eqn[2] has a
\{ pop_up_list(["?","horizontal","vertical","none"]) \}
asymptote with equation \{ ans_rule(10) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("equations") \}
$BR
$BR
$BITALIC Hint:  Recall that a horizontal asymptote is expressed by an equation for a horizontal line of the form $BBOLD y = k $EBOLD and a vertical asymptote is expressed by an equation for a vertical line of the form $BBOLD x = k${EBOLD}.  Your answer must therefore include a variable (x or y), an equal sign, and a specific value for k.${EITALIC}

END_TEXT


#######################################
#  Answer evaluation

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

ANS( str_cmp($type[0]) );
ANS( $ans[0]->cmp() );
ANS( str_cmp($type[1]) );
ANS( $ans[1]->cmp() );
ANS( str_cmp($type[2]) );
ANS( $ans[2]->cmp() );

#ANS( str_cmp($type[0]) );
